"NOT FOUND"|"discessisset. The change to historic sequence is very abrupt, since the difference in the meaning of the tenses between interfecerit and discessisset is very slight, if any. Perhaps the former puts a merely supposed case, the latter a definite proposal; i.e. ***Supposing I were to kill you,*** compared with *** If you will go away,*** and so corresponding respectively to el with the optative and ihv with the subjunctive in Greek."

"NOT FOUND"|"arcem. Predicate with efficit; ***makes into a citadel.***magnis nocturnis***itineribus. ***Forced marches by night and day.*** Here, as in 18, 6, two epithets are used without a conjunction, referring to one noun, because one of them (nocturnis) makes up one notion with the noun, ***a night march.***praesidium. *** A garrison. ***39."

"NOT FOUND"|"equites. Nominative to relinquwU, consectati agreeing with it."

"NOT FOUND"|"Huic legioni***confidebat. Confido in Caesar generally is followed by a dative of a person trusted to, an ablative of a thing trusted in. E.g. confidere natura loci, III. 9, 3."

"NOT FOUND"|"habeat. The return to the primary tenses is perhaps for the sake of keeping the sense of habeat clear, as being a present-imperfect,. i.e. denoting an incompleted action in the present, *** is keeping.*** The imperfect in oratio obliqua corresponds to the perfect (aorist) as well as the present and past- imperfect of oratio recta. See note on Reported Speech, III. note (4)."

